config file age. If the config file last modified time is older than the threshold, this rull will generate an alert. \u003c/maml:para\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:para\u003eThis might mean that the agent is stale and not updating config, and needs to have the cache flushed.\u003c/maml:para\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:para\u003eThis might mean the config service on the management server is not processing config changes.\u003c/maml:para\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:para\u003eThis might mean that no changes have been processed for the agent and you just need a longer default threshold.\u003c/maml:para\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:para\u003eThe rule runs a script once per day by default, and does not initialize immediately after the health service starts up, to allow time for the config file to update on agents that have been down for a considerable amount of time to reduce false alerts.\u003c/maml:para\u003e\r"," \u003c/maml:section\u003e\r"," \u003c/MamlContent\u003e\r"," \u003c/KnowledgeArticle\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:section xmlns:maml=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/maml/2004/10\"\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:title\u003eSummary\u003c/maml:title\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:para\u003eThis monitor checks the Operations DB size and transaction log size.\u003c/maml:para\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:para\u003eIf the OperationsManager database is less than a threshold in size it will be unhealthy.\u003c/maml:para\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:para\u003eIf the OperationsManager TLOG is less than a threshold in size it will be unhealthy.\u003c/maml:para\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:para\u003eThe threshold settings are overrideable.\u003c/maml:para\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:para\u003eThe default settings are 30GB for DB and 15GB for log. You should set these to your minimum size expected, to monitor when someone changes the DB size, or log file size too small.\u003c/maml:para\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:para\u003eSee: https://blogs.technet.microsoft.com/kevinholman/2016/10/22/opsmgr-2016-quickstart-deployment-guide/\u003c/maml:para\u003e\r"," \u003c/maml:section\u003e\r"," \u003c/MamlContent\u003e\r"," \u003c/KnowledgeArticle\u003e\r"," \u003cKnowledgeArticle ElementID=\"SCOM.Health.RegKeyExists.AgentOnManagementServer.Monitor\" Visible=\"true\"\u003e\r"," \u003cMamlContent\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:section xmlns:maml=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/maml/2004/10\"\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:title\u003eSummary\u003c/maml:title\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:para\u003eThis monitor inspects the registry to see if an agent has been installed on a Management Server.\u003c/maml:para\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:para\u003eThis is a VERY bad condition, as agents will cause the Management Server service to restart every 10 minutes, causing resource pool instability. This is because agents will restart the Healthservice anytime the MonitoringHost.exe process, or Healthservice.exe process use a large amount of memory or handles. That is a normal condition on a management server.\u003c/maml:para\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:para\u003eIn general, it is not a best practice to place agents on management servers.\u003c/maml:para\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:para\u003eTo recover from this situation, delete the \"Agent Management Groups\" key at: HKLM:\\\\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Microsoft Operations Manager\\3.0\\Agent Management Groups\u003c/maml:para\u003e\r"," \u003c/maml:section\u003e\r"," \u003c/MamlContent\u003e\r"," \u003c/KnowledgeArticle\u003e\r"," \u003cKnowledgeArticle ElementID=\"SCOM.Health.RegValueContent.CommandTimeoutSeconds.Monitor\" Visible=\"true\"\u003e\r"," \u003cMamlContent\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:section xmlns:maml=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/maml/2004/10\"\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:title\u003eSummary\u003c/maml:title\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:para\u003eThis monitor checks the value for a registry value that optimizes management servers for large environments.\u003c/maml:para\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:para\u003eHKLM\\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Microsoft Operations Manager\\3.0\\Data Warehouse\\\u003c/maml:para\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:para\u003eREG_DWORD Decimal Value: Command Timeout Seconds = 1800\u003c/maml:para\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:para\u003eSCOM 2016 existing registry value: (not preset)\u003c/maml:para\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:para\u003eSCOM 2016 default code value: 600\u003c/maml:para\u003e\r"," \u003cmaml:para\u003eDescription: This helps with dataset maintenance as the default timeout of 10 minutes is often too short. Setting this to a longer value helps reduce the 31552 events you might see with standard database maintenance. This is a very common issue. http://blogs.technet.com/b/kevinholman/archive/2010/08/30/the-31552-event-or-why-is-my-data-warehouse-server-consuming-so-much-cpu.aspx This should be adjusted to however long it takes aggregations or other maintenance to run in your environment. Setting this value to allow for one full day to deploy the script resolves most customer issues. # Assign script name variable for use in event logging.
# Starting Script section - All scripts get this
# Gather the start time of the script
#Set variable to be used in logging events
#Log script event that we are starting task
# Connect to and then Query the database
# Check for errors connecting to SQL
$momapi.LogScriptEvent($ScriptName,$EventID,1,"`n FATAL ERROR: There was an attempting to connect to and query SQL. `n Terminating script. `n Error is: ($Error).")
# Set the output to a variable

$momapi.LogScriptEvent($ScriptName,$EventID,1,"`n FATAL ERROR: There was an error getting records from SQL or no records were returned. `n Number of rows returned: ($RowsCount). `n Terminating script.")
# Set Result to default to a good condition which will be overwritten if a bad condition is found

$momapi.LogScriptEvent($ScriptName,$EventID,0,"`n Results: ($FinalResult). `n AlertDaysRetained: ($AlertRetentionDays) `n AlertDaysExpected: ($AlertDays) `n EventDaysRetained: ($EventRetentionDays) `n EventDaysExpected: ($EventDays) `n PerfRawDaysRetained: ($PerfRawRetentionDays) `n PerfRawDaysExpected: ($PerfRawDays) `n PerfHourlyDaysRetained: ($PerfHourlyRetentionDays) `n PerfHourlyDaysExpected: ($PerfHourlyDays) `n PerfDailyDaysRetained: ($PerfDailyRetentionDays) `n PerfDailyDaysExpected: ($PerfDailyDays) `n StateRawDaysRetained: ($StateRawRetentionDays) `n StateRawDaysExpected: ($StateRawDays) `n StateHourlyDaysRetained: ($StateHourlyRetentionDays) `n StateHourlyDaysExpected: ($StateHourlyDays) `n StateDailyDaysRetained: ($StateDailyRetentionDays) `n StateDailyDaysExpected: ($StateDailyDays)")
#Log an event for script ending and total execution time.

#Log script event that we are starting task
# Connect to local SCOM Management Group Section
# I have found this to be the most reliable method to load SCOM modules for scripts running on Management Servers
# Import the OperationsManager module and connect to the management group
$momapi.LogScriptEvent($ScriptName,$EventID,1,"`n FATAL ERROR: Unable to load OperationsManager module or unable to connect to Management Server. `n Terminating script. `n Error is: ($Error).")
$momapi.LogScriptEvent($ScriptName,$EventID,2,"`n The OperationsManager Administrators Role contains the default BUILTIN\Administrators. `n Role contains: ($SCOMAdmins).")
$momapi.LogScriptEvent($ScriptName,$EventID,0,"`n The OperationsManager Administrators Role does not contain the default BUILTIN\Administrators. `n Role contains: ($SCOMAdmins).")
#Log an event for script ending and total execution time.

# Assign script name variable for use in event logging.
# Starting Script section - All scripts get this
# Gather the start time of the script

$SQLQuery1 = "USE tempdb; SELECT name, physical_name FROM sys.database_files WHERE NOT data_space_id=0"
# Connect to and then Query the database

$momapi.LogScriptEvent($ScriptName,$EventID,1,"`n FATAL ERROR: There was an attempting to connect to and query SQL. `n Terminating script. `n Error is: ($Error).")
# Set the output to a variable

$momapi.LogScriptEvent($ScriptName,$EventID,1,"`n FATAL ERROR: There was an error getting records from SQL or no records were returned. `n Number of objects returned: ($RowsCount). `n Terminating script.")
#This is bad. Throw bag that the tempDB file count is greater than 8 files
$momapi.LogScriptEvent($ScriptName,$EventID,2,"`n TempDB should not have more than 8 files. `n TempDBFileCount: ($TempDBFileCount).")
# Bad. The tempDB file count is 1. The tempDB is not optimized for a multi CPU server
$momapi.LogScriptEvent($ScriptName,$EventID,2,"`n TempDB database is a single file. TempDB should have the same number of files as logical CPUs. `n TempDBFileCount: ($TempDBFileCount).")
#Assume Good. TempDB filecount is greater than 1 and less than 8
$momapi.LogScriptEvent($ScriptName,$EventID,0,"`n TempDB file count is ($TempDBFileCount). `n TempDB should have the same number of files as logical CPUs.")
